Reasoning: The paper discusses the effects of information overload on online social media users and their behavior, which falls under the category of social media and social networks. Therefore, cs.SI (Social and Information Networks) is the most likely sub-category. The paper also uses an agent-based model to simulate online conversation dynamics, which falls under the category of simulation and modeling, making cs.SD (Software Engineering) another likely sub-category. Additionally, the paper discusses the impact of information overload on the spread of (dis)information, which could fall under the categories of cybersecurity (cs.CY) and human-computer interaction (cs.CE). Finally, the paper discusses the observed phenomena of online conversations, which could fall under the category of computational social science (cs.SOC).
